"Brovkin V., Petoukhov V., Claussen M., Bauer E., Archer D., Jaeger C.","Geoengineering climate by stratospheric sulfur injections: Earth system vulnerability to technological failure",2009,"Climatic Change","92","3-4",,"243","259",,,10.1007/s10584-008-9490-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58549098890&partnerID=40&md5=f120d218311dabc59530daa9d39459fd","Max-Planck-Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany; Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, P.O. Box 601203, Potsdam 14412, Germany; Meteorological Institute, University Hamburg, Bundesstr. 55, Hamburg 20146, Germany; Department of Geophysical Sciences, University of Chicago, 5734 S Ellis Ave, Chicago, IL 60637, United States","Brovkin, V., Max-Planck-Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany; Petoukhov, V., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, P.O. Box 601203, Potsdam 14412, Germany; Claussen, M., Max-Planck-Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany, Meteorological Institute, University Hamburg, Bundesstr. 55, Hamburg 20146, Germany; Bauer, E., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, P.O. Box 601203, Potsdam 14412, Germany; Archer, D., Department of Geophysical Sciences, University of Chicago, 5734 S Ellis Ave, Chicago, IL 60637, United States; Jaeger, C., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research, P.O. Box 601203, Potsdam 14412, Germany","We use a coupled climate-carbon cycle model of intermediate complexity to investigate scenarios of stratospheric sulfur injections as a measure to compensate for CO2-induced global warming. The baseline scenario includes the burning of 5,000 GtC of fossil fuels. A full compensation of CO2-induced warming requires a load of about 13 MtS in the stratosphere at the peak of atmospheric CO2 concentration. Keeping global warming below 2°C reduces this load to 9 MtS. Compensation of CO 2 forcing by stratospheric aerosols leads to a global reduction in precipitation, warmer winters in the high northern latitudes and cooler summers over northern hemisphere landmasses. The average surface ocean pH decreases by 0.7, reducing the calcifying ability of marine organisms. Because of the millennial persistence of the fossil fuel CO2 in the atmosphere, high levels of stratospheric aerosol loading would have to continue for thousands of years until CO2 was removed from the atmosphere. A termination of stratospheric aerosol loading results in abrupt global warming of up to 5°C within several decades, a vulnerability of the Earth system to technological failure. © 2008 The Author(s).",,"Aerosols; Atmospherics; Climate change; Fossil fuels; Global warming; Marine biology; Sulfur; Sulfur compounds; Upper atmosphere; Aerosol loading; Carbon cycling; Earth systems; Geoengineering; Intermediate complexity; Marine organisms; Surface oceans; Atmospheric aerosols; aerosol; carbon cycle; carbon dioxide; climate modeling; complexity; fossil fuel; global warming; Northern Hemisphere; stratosphere; sulfur",,,,,,"Archer, D.E., Modeling the calcite lysocline (1991) J Geophys Res, 96, p. 17. , 037-017, 050; Archer, D., (2007) Global Warming: Understanding the Forecast, p. 208. , Blackwell; Archer, D., Brovkin, V., Millennial atmospheric lifetime of anthropogenic CO2 (2008) Clim Change, , doi: 10.1007/s10584-008-9413-1; Archer, D., Kheshgi, H., Maierreimer, E., Multiple timescales for neutralization of fossil fuel CO2 (1997) Geophys Res Lett, 24, pp. 405-408; Bala, G., Caldeira, K., Mirin, A., Wickett, M., Delire, C., Multicentury changes to the global climate and carbon cycle: Results from a coupled climate and carbon cycle model (2005) J Climate, 18, pp. 4531-4544; Bengtsson, L., Geo-engineering to confine climate change: Is it at all feasible? (2006) Clim Change, 77, pp. 229-234; Broecker, W.S., Peng, T.H., The role of CaCO3 compensation in the glacial to interglacial atmospheric CO2 change (1987) Glob Biogeochem Cycles, 1, pp. 15-29; Brovkin, V., Bendtsen,